Where to start on this one. Do I start with the fact that no one could get an order into the guys behind the counter because they couldn't speak English? Or do I start with the unbelievably disgusting food they were serving? Unfortunately this was the only 24-hour place that we could find right where we were. I should have just not eaten. Apparently it's normal to have 50 loaves of wheat bread and nothing else also. our sandwiches are screwed up because of course the guy had no idea what we were saying because he could not speak the language. This was also not just us this was also everyone in line in front of us. Everyone was very frustrated and everyone's sandwiches were being made wrong. unfortunate that Subway would hire such a confidence behind the counter. There were two people working and neither one of them could speak to anyone in anything but a very broken English but they spoke to each other and were obviously mocking the customers. Absolutely terrible experience. I will probably avoid Subway for a long time

In this review, I attempt as a new Baltimore resident, to explain the dynamics at this downtown Subway, a franchise, with predominantly Indian employees, catering to a broad mix of clients including downtown city or business employees, well to do travelers from aboard or domestic Americas, groups from after Orioles games, intoxicated bar traffic, homeless and drug addicts who may or may not have money and may or may not be high, happy or angry, and then inner harbor residents like me who are strange.  In serving this complex mix of clientele, employees face the challenges of classifing people based on variables that are beyond themselves.  Classism, race, and gender might be considered.   Under these challenges, sometimes with the help of a security guard, employees continue to try to deliver quality service, 24/7, and overall do alright.

So I came in after an unfavorable experience at bubba gump down the street and didn’t eat. I walked in was greeted by the two gentleman behind the counter could tell they were both happy. As I’m about to order a young kid walks in yelling demanding cookies and to be served to him in a specific manner and could tell the kid was agitated. The two young men behind the counter did as they would with any other customer and take their order and receive payment. I chose to let them take care of the kid to just get him out of the store ASAP. I could not commend how relaxed and professional the two workers were and how nice they were. I hope the owner of this subway knows how lucky he is to have these two guys working for him in the professional manner they composed themselves not only representing themselves but the store aswell. And I hope Subway itself sees this review.
